#Text=Part 7
#Text=It was rather less than a week after that walk that Capes came and sat down beside Ann Veronica for their customary talk in the lunch hour .

#Text=He took a handful of almonds and raisins that she held out to him -- for both these young people had given up the practice of going out for luncheon -- and kept her hand for a moment to kiss her finger-tips .
#Text=He did not speak for a moment .
#Text=“ Well ? ” she said .
#Text=“ I say ! ” he said , without any movement .
#Text=“ Let ’s go . ”
#Text=“ Go ! ”
#Text=She did not understand him at first , and then her heart began to beat very rapidly .
#Text=“ Stop this -- this humbugging , ” he explained .
#Text=“ It ’s like the Picture and the Bust .
#Text=I ca n’t stand it .
#Text=Let ’s go .
#Text=Go off and live together -- until we can marry .
#Text=Dare you ? ”
#Text=“ Do you mean NOW ? ”
#Text=“ At the end of the session .
#Text=It ’s the only clean way for us .
#Text=Are you prepared to do it ? ”
#Text=Her hands clenched .
#Text=“ Yes , ” she said , very faintly .
#Text=And then : “ Of course !
#Text=Always .
#Text=It is what I have wanted , what I have meant all along . ”
#Text=She stared before her , trying to keep back a rush of tears .
#Text=Capes kept obstinately stiff , and spoke between his teeth .
#Text=“ There ’s endless reasons , no doubt , why we should n’t , ” he said .
#Text=“ Endless .
#Text=It ’s wrong in the eyes of most people .
#Text=For many of them it will smirch us forever ... .
#Text=You DO understand ? ”
#Text=“ Who cares for most people ? ” she said , not looking at him .
#Text=“ I do .
#Text=It means social isolation -- struggle . ”
#Text=“ If you dare -- I dare , ” said Ann Veronica .
#Text=“ I was never so clear in all my life as I have been in this business . ”
#Text=She lifted steadfast eyes to him .
#Text=“ Dare ! ” she said .
#Text=The tears were welling over now , but her voice was steady .
#Text=“ You ’re not a man for me -- not one of a sex , I mean .
#Text=You ’re just a particular being with nothing else in the world to class with you .
#Text=You are just necessary to life for me .
#Text=I ’ve never met any one like you .
#Text=To have you is all important .
#Text=Nothing else weighs against it .
#Text=Morals only begin when that is settled .
#Text=I sha’ n’t care a rap if we can never marry .
#Text=I ’m not a bit afraid of anything -- scandal , difficulty , struggle ... .
#Text=I rather want them .
#Text=I do want them . ”
#Text=“ You ’ll get them , ” he said .
#Text=“ This means a plunge . ”
#Text=“ Are you afraid ? ”
#Text=“ Only for you !
#Text=Most of my income will vanish .
#Text=Even unbelieving biological demonstrators must respect decorum ; and besides , you see -- you were a student .
#Text=We shall have -- hardly any money . ”
#Text=“ I do n’t care . ”
#Text=“ Hardship and danger . ”
#Text=“ With you ! ”
#Text=“ And as for your people ? ”
#Text=“ They do n’t count .
#Text=That is the dreadful truth .
#Text=This -- all this swamps them .
#Text=They do n’t count , and I do n’t care . ”
#Text=Capes suddenly abandoned his attitude of meditative restraint .
#Text=“ By Jove ! ” he broke out , “ one tries to take a serious , sober view .
#Text=I do n’t quite know why .
#Text=But this is a great lark , Ann Veronica !
#Text=This turns life into a glorious adventure ! ”
#Text=“ Ah ! ” she cried in triumph .
#Text=“ I shall have to give up biology , anyhow .
#Text=I ’ve always had a sneaking desire for the writing-trade .
#Text=That is what I must do .
#Text=I can . ”
#Text=“ Of course you can . ”
#Text=“ And biology was beginning to bore me a bit .
#Text=One research is very like another ... .
#Text=Latterly I ’ve been doing things ... .
#Text=Creative work appeals to me wonderfully .
#Text=Things seem to come rather easily ... . But that , and that sort of thing , is just a day-dream .
#Text=For a time I must do journalism and work hard ... .
#Text=What is n’t a day-dream is this : that you and I are going to put an end to flummery -- and go ! ”
#Text=“ Go ! ” said Ann Veronica , clenching her hands .
#Text=“ For better or worse . ”
#Text=“ For richer or poorer . ”
#Text=She could not go on , for she was laughing and crying at the same time .
#Text=“ We were bound to do this when you kissed me , ” she sobbed through her tears .
#Text=“ We have been all this time -- Only your queer code of honor -- Honor !
#Text=Once you begin with love you have to see it through . ”
#Text=CHAPTER THE FIFTEENTH
#Text=THE LAST DAYS AT HOME
#Text=Part 1
#Text=They decided to go to Switzerland at the session ’s end .
#Text=“ We ’ll clean up everything tidy , ” said Capes ... .
#Text=For her pride ’s sake , and to save herself from long day-dreams and an unappeasable longing for her lover , Ann Veronica worked hard at her biology during those closing weeks .
#Text=She was , as Capes had said , a hard young woman .
#Text=She was keenly resolved to do well in the school examination , and not to be drowned in the seas of emotion that threatened to submerge her intellectual being .

#Text=Nevertheless , she could not prevent a rising excitement as the dawn of the new life drew near to her -- a thrilling of the nerves , a secret and delicious exaltation above the common circumstances of existence .

#Text=Sometimes her straying mind would become astonishingly active -- embroidering bright and decorative things that she could say to Capes ; sometimes it passed into a state of passive acquiescence , into a radiant , formless , golden joy .

#Text=She was aware of people -- her aunt , her father , her fellow-students , friends , and neighbors -- moving about outside this glowing secret , very much as an actor is aware of the dim audience beyond the barrier of the footlights .
#Text=They might applaud , or object , or interfere , but the drama was her very own .
#Text=She was going through with that , anyhow .
#Text=The feeling of last days grew stronger with her as their number diminished .
#Text=She went about the familiar home with a clearer and clearer sense of inevitable conclusions .
#Text=She became exceptionally considerate and affectionate with her father and aunt , and more and more concerned about the coming catastrophe that she was about to precipitate upon them .

#Text=Her aunt had a once exasperating habit of interrupting her work with demands for small household services , but now Ann Veronica rendered them with a queer readiness of anticipatory propitiation .

#Text=She was greatly exercised by the problem of confiding in the Widgetts ; they were dears , and she talked away two evenings with Constance without broaching the topic ; she made some vague intimations in letters to Miss Miniver that Miss Miniver failed to mark .
#Text=But she did not bother her head very much about her relations with these sympathizers .
